# Nuxt UI Components

Use **Nuxt UI** components wherever possible instead of custom HTML or raw Tailwind. This keeps the app consistent, accessible, and aligned with the design system.

## Component-first policy

- Prefer Nuxt UI components over custom markup (e.g. `UButton` over `<button>`, `UInput` over `<input>`, `UCard` over custom cards).
- Use Nuxt UI layout primitives for structure: `UApp`, `UHeader`, `UMain`, `UFooter`, `USeparator`.
- Use Iconify icons via the `icon` prop (e.g. `icon="i-lucide-home"`, `icon="i-simple-icons-github"`).

## Using the Nuxt UI MCP server

Before implementing a custom component or guessing API, use the **Nuxt UI MCP server** to find the right component and usage:

1. **Find components** – Use the MCP tools to search by category or name (e.g. form, button, modal) so you pick an existing Nuxt UI component.
2. **Read docs** – Use the MCP to get the component’s usage, examples, and recommended patterns.
3. **Check API** – Use the MCP to get props, slots, and events so you use the component correctly.

Relevant MCP actions: list/search components by category, get component documentation and examples, get component metadata (props, slots, events). Prefer these over guessing or copying from external sites.

## Styling and theme

- Rely on Nuxt UI theming via `app.config.ts` (e.g. `ui` config, color mode, theme tokens). Avoid one-off inline styles or arbitrary Tailwind overrides for things the design system already covers.
- Use Nuxt UI props for variants (`variant`, `color`, `size`) instead of custom classes when the component supports them.

## Example

```vue
<!-- Prefer Nuxt UI -->
<UButton icon="i-lucide-plus" variant="solid" color="primary" />
<UInput v-model="query" placeholder="Search..." />

<!-- Avoid custom-only equivalents when a Nuxt UI component exists -->
<button class="rounded bg-primary px-4 py-2">...</button>
```
